where the functions $F_{1}(q^{2})$ and $F_{2}(q^{2})$ are called the form factors and $q^{\nu}:=p'^{\nu}-p^{\nu}$ is the four-momentum transfer at the vertex. At radiative corrections, the information concerning to vertex corrections are all contained in $F_{1}(q^{2})$ and $F_{2}(q^{2})$. So, computing the vertex correction at one-loop level provide us the following form factors:

\begin{eqnarray}
&&F_{1}(q^{2})\,=\,\frac{\alpha}{2\pi}\int^{1}_{0}dx\int^{1}_{0}dy\int^{1}_{0}dz \; \delta(1-x-y-z)\nonumber\\
&&\times\left\{ \mbox{ln}\left[\frac{(1-z)^{2}m^{2}-xyq^{2}+zM^{2}}{(1-z)^{2}m^{2}-xyq^{2}}\right]+\right.\nonumber\\
&&\left.+\frac{z\,\left[m^{2}(1-4z+z^{2})+(1-x)(1-y)q^{2}\right]}{\left[(1-z)^{2}m^{2}-xyq^{2}\right]
\left[z+(1-z)^{2}\frac{m^{2}}{M^{2}}-xy\frac{q^{2}}{M^{2}}\right]} \right \},\nonumber\\
&&\\
&&\label{f2}
F_{2}(q^{2})\,=\,\frac{\alpha}{\pi}\int^{1}_{0}dx\int^{1}_{0}dy\int^{1}_{0}dz \,\, z^{2}(1-z)\nonumber\\
&&\times\frac{\delta(1-x-y-z)}{\left[(1-z)^{2}-xy\frac{q^{2}}{m^{2}}\right]\left[z+(1-z)^{2}\frac{m^{2}}{M^{2}}-xy\frac{q^{2}}{M^{2}}\right]}.
\end{eqnarray}


From $F_{1}(q^{2})$ and $F_{2}(q^{2})$ is clear that ultraviolet divergences do not affect the vertex corrections. The $F_{2}(q^{2})$ form factor when $q^{2} \rightarrow 0$ is related to deviation from the electron magnetic moment standard prediction of the Dirac equation. 





